Interlude<br>
Authors:  Esmalyn (pseudonym)    Millikin Erreene (pseudonymn)<br>
<br>
After shaking the strange feeling from her hands after her latest attempt at spellcasting, Millikin strolled over to the amphitheater for duels in the Bazaar.  She had seen a certain rogue lurking in the crowds earlier, likely picking through the pockets of the unwary.  Whistling to herself, her hand closed around a note she kept folded up in her pocket that reminded her of why she was seeking out Esmalyn now that her other preparations were underway.<br>
<br>
Cheers erupted to signal the end of a match as several runners moved out with a stretcher to remove the troll warrior lying on the ground, an arrow imbedded in his side.  Roses were thrown to the feet of the victor as he bowed gallantly on his way out to make room for the next combatants.  The ranger caught sight of her quarry, currently dawdling up the stands, her cloak whispering over the marble. Once the Tier'Dal decided on a seat, Millikin casually walked up whistling.  Esmalyn's keen hearing discerned the notes of the tune and while she didn't know it by name, she knew the ranger who was fond of whistling it from time to time.<br>
<br>
&quot;Vendui, elg' hasek,&quot; the Tier'Dal rogue sighed at her approach.  &quot;Lu'oh phuul dos?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I'm doing well.  And yourself?&quot;  Millikin continued whistling, knowing perfectly well Esmalyn did not really care how she was, but she went along with the minor civilities for the time being.<br>
<br>
&quot;I was well.&quot;  Esmalyn finally bothered to look over at the Feir`Dal, red eyes flickering.  &quot;Why have you come here?  You reek of marsh and grass.&quot;<br>
<br>
Millikin took a deep breath.  Finally the formalities have dispensed, down to business.<br>
<br>
&quot;Actually it's pine, not like you would be able to recognize the scent, but to cut to the chase, I need something from you.  You know of the Shissar, I presume?  At least of their existence, general appearance, and capabilities.<br>
<br>
Esmalyn reached up and pushed back her hood. Shoulder-length, white hair spilled out. &quot;They worm around The Grey, that airless plain.&quot;  She paused for a moment.  &quot;You are desperate.&quot; <br>
<br>
The sound of cymbals announced the start of a new match and Millikin turned to regard the latest combatants.  Two wizards were currently in the process of summoning energies to launch their attack.  Formal bets were called and coins changed hands.<br>
<br>
&quot;Not hardly,&quot; Millikin replied.  &quot;Simply asking you is what's most convenient at this time.&quot;  She did not turn to face the rogue until after the first wave of flaming rain descended upon one of the wizards scorching the ground but leaving him relatively unscathed.  &quot;I need a fast acting and fatal poison capable of killing a Shissar introduced by arrow or sword edge.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;This is new territory.  How much is this poison worth to you?&quot;  Esmalyn turned her attention back to the wizards' duel.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have components already to work with,&quot; Millikin replied. <br>
<br>
&quot;Is this a trap you have in store for me, payback for breaking into your flat?&quot; Esmalyn asked, sliding her gaze over to the Feir`Dal once more.<br>
<br>
&quot;No.  But since you brought that up...&quot; Millikin paused momentarily before continuing.  Though the ranger still continued her association on occasion with the rogue, Millikin had not forgotten (or forgiven) the incident where the dark elf thief had sneaked into her room and stolen a medallion piece from her.  The ranger simply bided her time, knowing eventually one day Esmalyn would be rewarded in full measure for her deceit.  As far as the enchanter who had hired Esmalyn for the task, Millikin considered that her role was rewarded as deserved at the hands of the ranger.<br>
<br>
&quot;... I would be willing to forget about your role in it if you can manage to make this poison.  The Luhtmauyar D`Varr was not so fortunate.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The Luhtmauyar D`Varr should not let her self-worth impair her judgment.  You have not worked up the nerve to strike back at me.  Tell me, lorulm darthirii, how has this changed?&quot;  Despite her words of bravado, the Teir`Dal rogue went taut as she looked up in appraisal of the ranger.<br>
<br>
&quot;I could strike back at this very instance.  Or tomorrow.  Or next week.  I have the time,&quot; Millikin replied evenly.  <br>
<br>
&quot;I'll keep that in mind.&quot;  Esmalyn returned her attention to the fight.  Her facial expression schooled to neutrality as she relaxed somewhat.<br>
<br>
&quot;But I'm aware that you were simply one of Valdayana's flunkies, carrying out her orders.&quot;  Millikin took a tone of feigned innocent understanding.  &quot;Faced with the prospect of getting paid or risking her ire, most people of your caliber would take the money too.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;One of us is gaining notoriety as a lackey, lorulm darthirii, and I don't intend to travel down that path.&quot;  Esmalyn turned once again to look over at the ranger, the scar over her eye accentuating the sneer twisting her lips as she responded.  &quot;Either pay a wage or seek another pathetic rogue to do your bidding free of charge.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Are you even capable of making such a poison?  Aside from the fact that you do little more than steal from those you work with, I'm wondering if you are up to the task.  You can't even pilfer from a fungusbeast without getting caught.&quot;  Millikin couldn't resist adding the last statement for emphasis.  She could tell by Esmalyn's sudden vagueness that the comment struck a chord.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am versed in amounts, combinations; plants and fungi.  Injected, swallowed, or applied.  I could --&quot;  She paused, a bemused grin on her face.  &quot;You couldn't even keep a common thief from ransacking your home.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You didn't ransack 'my' home.&quot;  Millikin replied dryly.  The ranger did not consider the rented room in Shadowhaven her home by any stretch nor was she going to allow the rogue to think any jab she took to provoke her would have any effect or distract from the business at hand.  Either she could make the poison or she could not.  She had little time to continue this game of point-counterpoint.  &quot;Nor did you answer the question.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Don't interrupt me.&quot;  Esmalyn leaned back and looked up at Millikin.  &quot;I am capable of such a poison, although, I can't offer a set time.  A week at the most.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;A week at most to make it?&quot;  Millikin inquired.  Esmalyn nodded.  Millikin was not satisfied.  &quot;Five or seven days in Norrathian time?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Seven days in a Norrathian week, unless you've attuned yourself to Luclin's cycles beyond repair.&quot;  Esmalyn idly wondered if Millikin was representative of her race in overall stupidity.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm making sure the time frame is clear as water.&quot;  Millikin remarked, she was not going to be conned about Luclin versus Norrath time frames due to the lack of standard recognizable cycles of day and night on Norrath's moon.  &quot;How much?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Fifty platinum.  I know how thrifty you are.  Don't ask how, and doubt you carry more than ten gold on your person right now.&quot;  Esmalyn didn't miss a beat where money was concerned.  She pointed behind the ranger in the direction of the bank.  &quot;Half up front, the other half at production.  We can make a transfer at the bank now if you wish.&quot;  The rogue stood up to leave.<br>
<br>
&quot;What guarantee do I have it will work?&quot;  Millikin narrowed her eyes.  &quot;I don't particularly care for the prospect of paying fifty platinum for colored water.&quot;<br>
<br>
Esmalyn smirked and she canted her head to the side in response.  &quot;Presuming your samples are relatively fresh and I have enough to spare for a test, you can witness it in action yourself. You can even volunteer to have it tested on yourself, which, I wouldn't protest.&quot;  She walked past the ranger, quite confident in her position regarding this transaction.<br>
<br>
The ranger did not think the suggestion of a simple poison test was enough.  &quot;I need it to kill Shissar, not some rat you picked up in the sewers you roam.&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;We can test it on a Shissar.  I don't promise more than I can deliver.  Valdayana could tell you that.&quot;  Esmalyn replied over her shoulder.<br>
<br>
&quot;A moment...&quot;  Millikin paused then continued.  &quot;One third now.  The remaining two-thirds after the test sample proves worthwhile.  And you make it in three days... for sixty-five platinum.&quot;  <br>
<br>
&quot;Seventy platinum.&quot;  Esmalyn stopped and shifted her weight to turn midstep.  &quot;Materials, an alchemist if I need to hire one, trips to and from the Grey.&quot;  She ticked these off on her fingers.  &quot;Seventy platinum.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;It doesn't cost anything to reach the Grey.  And I'm supplying the materials already.&quot;  Millikin argued.<br>
<br>
&quot;You are rushing me.  I cannot account for accidents, however that may please you, or shortages from quick samples.  Seventy platinum for three days or fifty for seven.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Could you manage an accident after the test?  It would save me about forty-six platinum.&quot;  The ranger doesn't even bother to hide her grin.<br>
<br>
&quot;Dark powers help me, I can think of the perfect accident.&quot;  Esmalyn's poignant gaze fell upon the ranger.<br>
<br>
&quot;So long as its painful for you, I am not overly concerned about perfection,&quot; Millikin replied dryly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Its settled then.  Meet me at the bank and make ready thirty-five platinum.&quot;  Esmalyn turned on a booted heel and left the stadium, quickly disappearing from sight as Millikin headed towards the bank muttering about avaricious money-grubbing Teir`Dal.<br>
