<br>
     Millikin handed the four orbs over to Sontalak.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I found them all.&quot;  <br>
<br>
  &quot;So you did.&quot;  The ancient dragon answered response as he inspected each orb for flaws.  &quot;And you did not damage any of them either.&quot;  The dragon folded his wings slightly as he placed the four orbs into on of his clawed hands.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Is the fact that each one represents a different elemental force significant?&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Yes.  As I told you before, they contain an elemental force's essence to imbue into another person, Wood elf.  Now stand aside unless you wish to become charred.&quot;  The rust colored dragon flicked his tail once for emphasis and Millikin stepped back as Sontalak drew a deep intake of breath and then quickly expelled a blast of lava into his hand holding the orbs and quickly closed it around them.  Millikin watched as a pale orange nimbus surrounded the dragon's claws.  <br>
<br>
In moments Sontalak opened his hand to reveal a small flat crystalline disc bearing claw marks on the edges and the etchings of a fire dragon, wind dragon, water dragon, and an earth dragon on either side.  <br>
<br>
  &quot;Simply break it to release its power into yourself.&quot;  Sontalak handed the disc to Millikin.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Thank you.  But I was not going to use it myself.&quot;  Millikin replied as she took the offered disc.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Then why have you spent the past few weeks pestering me about the orb you found a while ago and wheedling under rocks and ash through the mountains of Skyfire for the others more recently?&quot;  Sontalak craned his neck to face the ranger, bringing himself eye level to her, his look of consternation caused the ranger to freeze in place.<br>
<br>
  &quot;It's for another.&quot;  Millikin stated uneasily when the dragon fear dissipated and she could think coherently enough to reply.  &quot;She's spent time going through books and scrolls in the Skyshrine and knows much of the Ring of Scale also.&quot;   Sontalak snorted at the mention of the Ring of Scale, an outcast sect of the Claws of Veeshan.  <br>
<br>
  &quot;I thought she might like something akin to this.&quot;  Millikin paused.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Then perhaps your friend should do the work to acquire it.&quot;  Sontalak rumbled once again.  The mental image brought a grin to Millikin's face though it quickly vanished.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I doubt she would lower herself to foraging, even if she could.&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Then why should she reap the benefits of your efforts, Ranger?&quot;<br>
<br>
     Millikin paused to consider that question.  Indeed why was she even wasting her time?  Chances are the gift would be spurned outright.  Or worse, viewed as a bribe.  She quickly pushed aside that line of thought by deciding she would simply steel herself for the likely insults and deal with them when the time came.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I suppose it is a means of requiting how I benefited from her efforts.&quot;   Millikin replied after a thoughtful pause.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I see.&quot;  Sontalak replied.<br>
<br>
  &quot;I'm not exactly adept with expressing my feelings.&quot;   The ranger explained.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Actions speak for themselves, Ranger.&quot;  Sontalak remarked as he looked out into the wasteland ahead of them.  &quot;Are you going to continue with stories of your exploits with your shaman friend on the moon or do I wait until next time?&quot;  Another time she would recount to the aged dragon of her most recent sojourn into the Sshraeshza temple but for now, Millikin beamed as she began to recount to the dragon one of her and Saldaria's earlier forays into the Grey battling the Shissar and golems just outside the temple.<br>
