<br>
<br>
     Millikin tended to take into consideration any personality criticisms made about her, even if she did not acknowledge them initially.  After some objective consideration of her behavior (if one taking into consideration their own traits can really be considered objective) and inquiries from those she did openly respect, the general consensus was that her somewhat somber outlook could be construed as such by those not familiar with the ranger's true nature.<br>
<br>
     Why did she care what the luhtmauyar thought of her?  Thinking rationally, the ranger knew perfectly well that Valdayana D`Varr held no regard for anyone but herself so why should her opinion of anyone (which is guaranteed to be low) matter.  Millikin herself wasn't sure if she held some small hope that the enchanter was not irredeemably evil.  She remembered Ashwith's warning that she could just as likely help someone out for the sheer feeling of power over them and not because she held a modicum of regard for them.  Though the warning made sense, the concept was foreign to Millikin.  Whenever she traveled or explored with others, she felt a sense of responsibility for their safety and took what means she could to ensure that they did survive.  How anyone could not share that sense of obligation was inconceivable to the ranger.  Was that not the entire purpose of working together?<br>
<br>
     Maybe Millikin respected the enchanter beyond the comprehension that she was extremely skilled in her field in spite of the enchanter's disparaging comments about her race, competence as a ranger, or personality.  Though how or why she had no clue.  Millikin hid the fact that sometimes Valdayana's comments bothered her by simply ignoring them or replying with a half-felt rejoinder of her own.  They technically shouldn't bother her because they were either said to simply provoke her or validly point out a fault.  And maybe the latter fact was what Millikin respected about her.  She didn't know for sure.<br>
<br>
     Millikin stared down at the crystalline disc lying on the table.  It took quite a bit of effort on her part to obtain the crystals to make it, and convince the dragon known as Sontalak to do so as well.  The ranger was not sure how she would react to the insulting rebuff that was likely to result from her offering it to the enchanter and the thought of simply sending it by courier was very appealing.  At least she wouldn't see the rejection firsthand.  The thought of the gift becoming impersonal though made her ultimately dismiss the idea of having it delivered.  Millikin decided to offer it firsthand and simply brace herself for the worst as she picked up the disc and slid it into her pocket as she headed out of her flat. <p>M. E.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/umillikinerreene.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Millikin Erreene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Arrowbringer </span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(6/15/02 8:40:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=27.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Curse</span><hr size=1> <br>
