Shiobahn Fyrestrike (formerly Goldbrooke) sat quietly upon a small blanket by the lakeside in her home town.  Above her loomed the guilds of the magical arts, her own designation included amongst them, and every so often she could hear the workings of different defensive spells coming from above.  Her momentary solitude was dedicated to toying with a pouch of runes, identifying each of the marks upon them to further her research for greater spells.  Quasqueton had promised her even greater runes when he returned back from his quest, but the days seemed to grow longer and longer in his absence.  It was in this moment of study and reflection that she distinctly heard the soft footfalls of the sure-footed ranger approaching her.<br>
<br>
A smile crept across the delicately defined high Elven face as she let the initial shock of the visit wear away, and Shio rose to her feet.  She stood taller than the ranger, though her frame more willowy, and her hair was quite obviously flame kissed by her deity of the arts, Solusek Ro, whom she called upon for the power of her spells.  She reached out her hands to the ranger as she spoke softly in the language of the elves "Creoso eska, tinu en'Tunare.  It is good to see you home cousin."  Millikin gripped her hands in return though her present mood was unreadable, as often it was, by her kin.  "Diol'lle, Shiobahn.  It is good to return once again."<br>
<br>
Shiobahn studied her a moment, certain there was a tale to be told, but not knowing when the ranger would tell it, if she decided to speak of it at all.  "We shall catch up over a glass of Elven wine.  The day is still early and the tavern is open across town.  Just allow me to pack my things."  Shio did not offer much room for argument, though then she rarely did.  She quickly bent down to retrieve her runes, pouring them back into a small pouch that hung from her belt.  She carried a small myriad of trinkets this way, including a finely crafted golden bowl bearing a few small dings in the bottom which hinted at the fact she was not afraid to swing it at something if one of her spells was going awry, no matter how futile the attempt was.  Tucking her blanket into a backpack she then set off on foot along side her cousin to the tavern.<br>
<br>
